Guiding Question

Are higher salaries associated with better performance for NFL quarterbacks?

Become Acquainted with Data Source

This is a data source from Kaggle, containing 5,523 cases of NFL player salary data. This was published by Dr.Hax and was most recently updated about 10 months ago (around June of 2019). This data is important for the business side of the NFL. I plan mainly to use the average annual salary variable, but I could also use some of the other variables such as the total salary, total guaranteed salary, and fully guaranteed salary variables.

Become Acquainted with Data Source

This is a data source from ESPN, containing 50 cases of NFL quarterback statistics in the most recent regular season (2019). This data tells more of a story about how well the players performed in the most recent season, and I will use this data to compare with their salaries and see if the players matched up to their pay grade. I will mainly use the touchdowns, total yards, average yards per game, QBR, and rating variables for their positive performances, but it may be important to take the interception variable into account as well.

PassingStats %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = interceptions)) + geom_density() + geom_rug()

The above graph shows a fairly spread out depiction of the number of interceptions thrown over the year. The density plot shows that the most frequent amount of interceptions thrown for the year was less than 10, but this accounts for injuries and quarterbacks getting benched over the course of the year as well. With 32 NFL teams and 50 quarterbacks in the data set, this density plot was bound to be pushed to the left at least slightly.

PassingStats %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = touchdowns, y = total_yds)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()

The above graph shows me that the total yards and number of touchdowns for quarterbacks in the 2019 NFL season have a fairly strong positive correlation. However, this relationship isnt exactly linear, as it tails off at the higher end. This could happen for multiple reasons, but my preliminary guess would be that the number of touchdowns has more variability than the number of yards thrown for in a season. This is shown by the smoother, as the confidence band gets significantly wider at the higher end of the data. This makes sense because yards should accumulate over the season to the typical average for the player, while touchdown numbers could fluctuate per season depending on other factors such as percent of time in the redzone and etc.

PassingStats %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = interceptions, y = total_yds)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()

This graph shows me that there is a slight positive relationship between interceptions and total yards thrown for in a season. This relationship isnt as drastic as the one above, telling me that interceptions may have more to do with decision making rather than the circumstances that touchdowns have to do with. However, the positive relationship still makes sense because with more total yards you most likely have taken more attempts as well, giving more chances for interceptions to be thrown. There may be one outlier on the far right that is pulling the line of best fit downwards, as Jameis Winston threw a historically high number of interceptions (well above the second most interceptions last season).

PassingStats %>%
  filter(interceptions > 29)

After following this past NFL season fairly closely, I know that this number of interceptions is legitimate. For this reason, I will not remove the possible outlier.

Using both Data Sources

The first thing I have noticed that may become a problem is the fact that the name variable for the two data sets contain different information. In the NFL_Salaries data table, the name is just the first and last name of the player. However, the name column in the PlayerStats data table contains their first and last name and their teams abbreviation. Before joining these two tables, I need to figure out how to split the team abbreviation from the name and create a separate variable for the team abbreviation. This would allow me to then join the two tables by the player names I am looking for.

Further Data Analysis

Grouped_Complete_Table <- Complete_Table %>%
  group_by(team.x) %>%
  summarise(total_tds = sum(touchdowns), total_ints = sum(interceptions), avg_salary = mean(avg_year), total_yards = sum(total_yds))
Grouped_Complete_Table
Grouped_Complete_Table %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = total_yards, y = avg_salary)) +  geom_text(aes(label = team.x, color = team.x)) + geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE)

The above graph shows a 3-variable scatterplot in which the x-axis has the total yards, the y-axis has the average salary, and the points are labeled and colored by the team name. The quarterbacks are grouped by team, so all 32 teams are respresented, but the data may contain the total information for two or more quarterbacks (due to injuries, benchings, etc.). I then added a line of best fit to show whether teams seemed to be overpaying or underpaying their quarterbacks based on the average for their performance level (total yards in the season). As you can see, teams like GB and SEA seem to have paid much more for their quarterbacks at a similar amount of total yards, but those two teams did in fact make the playoffs this past season. On the other hand, teams like TB and DAL seem to have paid very little for their quarterbacks that provided a much higher amount of total yards, but these two teams missed the playoffs this past season. This shows that yardage numbers are not the only factor that goes into good quarterback play; the quarterback must also elevate the team around him because football is a team sport.

Rich_Quarterback <- lm(avg_year >= 20000000 ~ age + QBR + completion_pct + touchdowns + interceptions, data = Complete_Table)

Here I am using machine learning to create a linear model. This model tells me that the age variable is significant at the 5% significance level, and the touchdowns variable is significant at the 10% significance level in predicting if a quarterbacks yearly salary is over $20,000,000. The age variable definitely makes sense, because young quarterbacks who were recently drafted are not qualified to be paid large amounts of money until they spend at least 4 years in the league. I am a little surprised that QBR isnt significant because that is the newest rating system in which quarterback play is graded (on a 100 point scale), so clearly the new method still isnt perfect. Of the quantitative variables (that have to do with performance, so not including age) selected for the model, touchdowns seem to be the best predictor of the bunch in order to predict average yearly salary for quarterbacks in the NFL today. However, this was still not significant at the 5% level, so we are not as certain as we would like that this variable is a great predictor.

In conclusion, many factors go into the decision for what to pay quarterbacks in the NFL today. As the years go on and inflation continues to drive prices up, quarterbacks are going to continue to make more and more money each free agency period. Agents are great at their jobs and they know how to get their guys to be paid like top tier quarterbacks, even though they may not be the best guy out there. With all of this being said, along with the analyses shown above, quarterbacks are generally paid according to their performance although it is not an exact science. The best way to win in todays world is to pay your supporting cast while your quarterback is still young and on his rookie contract, as shown by the current Super Bowl champion Kansas City Chiefs.
